          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The right lymphatic duct and the thoracic duct are the two terminal channels of the lymphatic system. Which body region is drained by the right lymphatic duct?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The entire right half of the body, including the right lower limb</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This is a common misconception. The right lymphatic duct drains only the right upper quadrant — the lower limbs and abdomen are served by the thoracic duct.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Right side of the head, neck, and thorax, and the right upper limb</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The right lymphatic duct has a limited territory — only the right upper quadrant. Everything else, including both lower limbs, drains via the thoracic duct into the left subclavian vein.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Both lower limbs and the pelvis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Both lower limbs and the pelvis are drained by the thoracic duct, which handles roughly three-quarters of the body's lymphatic drainage.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The left side of the head and neck only</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The left head and neck region is drained by the thoracic duct, not the right lymphatic duct. The right lymphatic duct serves only right-sided upper-body structures.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember: the thoracic duct drains roughly three-quarters of the body. The right lymphatic duct handles only the right side of the head, neck, thorax, and the right upper limb."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The right lymphatic duct serves a small but clinically important territory — the right upper quadrant only."
                }
              ],
