          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Lymphoedema characteristically produces progressive, non-pitting tissue swelling</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Lymphoedema characteristically produces progressive, non-pitting tissue swelling. What is the primary mechanism responsible?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Increased hydrostatic pressure in the venous system</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Raised venous hydrostatic pressure produces venous oedema, which is typically pitting. Lymphoedema has a fundamentally different mechanism involving trapped macromolecules.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Accumulation of large plasma proteins in the tissues, drawing water in by osmosis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Lymphatics are the only route for returning large proteins such as albumin from tissues to blood. When drainage fails, these proteins accumulate and exert osmotic pressure, pulling water into the interstitium and producing non-pitting swelling.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Excessive secretion of interstitial fluid by blood capillaries</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Blood capillaries filter fluid at a normal rate in lymphoedema. The problem lies on the drainage side — lymphatic vessels cannot clear the fluid and its protein content.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Obstruction of arterial blood supply to the affected region</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Arterial obstruction causes ischaemia, not oedema. Lymphoedema is specifically a failure of lymphatic drainage, not arterial supply.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The key point: lymphatics are the only vessels that remove large proteins from tissues. When they fail, trapped proteins draw in water osmotically, causing progressive non-pitting swelling."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The protein-trapping mechanism is what distinguishes lymphoedema from other forms of oedema and explains why it is non-pitting."
                }
              ],
